<section xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="syllabus-ma301">
	<title>Syllabus</title>

	<introduction>
		<p>
			Carefully review every item of this syllabus. By taking this course, you are agreeing
			to the polices laid out in this document. Let me know if you have any questions.
		</p>
	</introduction>

	<subsection label="ma301-general-info">
		<title>General</title>

		<xi:include href="./syllabus/common/instructor-info.ptx" />

		<subsubsection label="ma301-course-info">
			<title>Course Information</title>
			<p>
				<dl>
					<li><title>Course Description</title>
						<p>
							A study of vector analysis for scientists and engineers: vector fields, line integrals, conservative vector fields, Green's Theorem, parameterization of curves and surfaces, the Divergence Theorem, and Stokes' Theorem, together with an introduction to Fourier series, complex variables, and partial differential equations.
						</p>
					</li>
					<!-- TODO(geoff): confirm MA 301 room and meeting time for the current term (the 2015 syllabus gave none). -->
					<li><title>Meetings</title><p>Room/Time TBD</p></li>
					<li><title>Prerequisite</title><p>Grade of C or better in MA 215 and MA 311</p></li>
					<li><title>Department Head</title><p>COL Troy Siemers</p></li>
				</dl>
			</p>
		</subsubsection>
	</subsection>

	<subsection label="ma301-grades">
		<title>Grades &amp; Coursework</title>

		<!--
			TODO(geoff): GRADING SCHEME UNDECIDED — choose between (a) the
			traditional weighted scheme transcribed from the 2015 syllabus,
			rendered below as a provisional default, and (b) the
			proficiency-based grading (ODP / Pass–Not-yet) scheme used by
			the MA 311 template this file was adapted from. Both are
			supplied as ready-to-paste PreTeXt snippets in the PR body. The
			traditional scheme below is the authoritative 2015 content, NOT
			a final decision — replace this whole subsection with the PBG
			snippet if you prefer mastery grading.
		-->

		<subsubsection label="ma301-final-grade">
			<title>Final Grades</title>
			<p>
				Your final grade is a weighted average of the following components:
			</p>

			<table>
				<title>Grade Weights</title>
				<tabular bottom="minor" top="minor" left="minor" right="minor" halign="center">
					<col width="60%"/>
					<col width="40%"/>
					<row>
						<cell><term>Component</term></cell>
						<cell><term>Weight</term></cell>
					</row>
					<row><cell>Tests (3)</cell><cell>30%</cell></row>
					<row><cell>Homework</cell><cell>40%</cell></row>
					<row><cell>Final Exam</cell><cell>30%</cell></row>
				</tabular>
			</table>
		</subsubsection>

		<subsubsection label="ma301-tests">
			<title>Tests</title>
			<p>
				There will be three in-class tests over the course of the semester, together worth 30% of your final grade. Each test is a formal, points-based assessment covering the topics studied since the previous test. Test dates will be announced in class and/or posted on the class website.
			</p>
		</subsubsection>

		<subsubsection label="ma301-homework">
			<title>Homework</title>
			<p>
				Homework is worth 40% of your final grade and consists of both hand-written and online assignments.
			</p>
			<p>
				<term>Hand-written</term> assignments should be organized and rigorous — no scratch-work solutions. Due dates are announced in class and/or posted on the class website.
			</p>
			<p>
				<term>Online</term> homework is assigned for each topic we cover and must be submitted by the posted due date. Most problems require step-by-step work, so you should complete them on paper before entering final answers online. Problems may allow multiple attempts; if you struggle, use it as a chance to learn and ask for help before using all of your attempts.
			</p>
		</subsubsection>

		<subsubsection label="ma301-final">
			<title>Final Exam</title>
			<p>
				You will take a comprehensive, points-based final exam covering all topics from the course. It is worth 30% of your final grade.
			</p>
		</subsubsection>
	</subsection>

	<subsection label="ma301-topics">
		<title>Course Topics</title>

		<introduction>
			<p>
				The course centers on vector analysis, with additional topics selected from Fourier series, complex variables, and partial differential equations. The list below is tentative and subject to adjustment as the semester progresses.
			</p>
		</introduction>

		<table>
			<title>Course Topics</title>
			<tabular bottom="minor" top="minor" left="minor" right="minor">
				<col halign="left" valign="top" width="30%"/>
				<col halign="left" width="70%"/>
				<row>
					<cell><term>Unit</term></cell>
					<cell><term>Topics</term></cell>
				</row>
				<row>
					<cell><p>Vector Analysis</p></cell>
					<cell>
						<p>
							<line>Vector fields</line>
							<line>Line integrals</line>
							<line>Conservative vector fields</line>
							<line>Green's Theorem</line>
							<line>Parameterization of lines and surfaces</line>
							<line>The Divergence Theorem</line>
							<line>Stokes' Theorem</line>
						</p>
					</cell>
				</row>
				<row>
					<cell><p>Additional Topics</p></cell>
					<cell>
						<p>
							<line>Fourier series</line>
							<line>Complex variables</line>
							<line>Partial differential equations</line>
						</p>
					</cell>
				</row>
			</tabular>
		</table>

		<!--
			TODO(geoff): The 2015 syllabus opened MA 301 directly at vector
